Monday morning edition. For seven decades the church has served as the premier model of Protestant liberalism in the United States. Its history represents the movement from white Protestant hegemony to a multiracial and multiethnic church that has been at the vanguard of social justice advocacy, liberation theologies, gay and lesbian ministries, peace studies, ethnic and racial dialogue, and Jewish-Christian relations. A collaborative effort by a stellar team of scholars, The History of the Riverside Church in the City of New York offers a critical history of this unique institution on Manhattan's Upper West Side, including its cultural impact on New York City and beyond, its outstanding preachers, and its architecture, and assesses the shifting fortunes of religious progressivism in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNew York (N.Y.)xChurch history. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  achronicle.  ainformative.  ainstitution.  alandmark.  athorough.1 aCook, John W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCook, John Wesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudnut-Beumler, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHudnut-Beumler, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMamiya, Lawrence H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarty, Martin E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParis, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTisdale, Leonora Tubbs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081476713940